In [4]:
college.private.df <- filter(college.df, Private == "Yes")
hist(college.private.df$PhD, prob = TRUE, main = "PhD holders in Private Colleges", xlab = "Private Colleges", col = terrain.colors(10))
lines(density(college.private.df$PhD), col = "red", lwd = 3)

Private Colleges histogram is top-heavy on the right side since there is a clear peak of PhDs for more Private Colleges. It can be concluded that there are more Private Colleges with a lot of PhD faculty.

In [5]:
college.public.df <- filter(college.df, Private == "No")
hist(college.public.df$PhD, prob = TRUE, main = "PhD holders in Public Colleges", xlab = "Public Colleges", col = topo.colors(8))
lines(density(college.public.df$PhD), col = "red", lwd = 3)

Public Colleges histogram is also top-heavy even though the peak is closer t the center of the plot; this is due to the range of Public Colleges being a subset of the Private Colleges histogram's colleges range (0 and 20 are missing whuch can be assumed to be 0). Furthermore, there is a disprencancy in public colleges when it comes to PhD faculty since the density of PhDs arre .30 to .35 or less than .13.

The Histograms shows us how acceptance of 4 categories of colleges (Crossing Elite and Public). Both Non Elite Private and Public Colleges have a similar spread of acceptance in the sense that they are top-heavy with changes in ranges (might be a population problem). What suprising is the spread of acceptance for non-elite schools. Public schools have more colleges acceptance in this case and might be a bias for the colleges that rank at the lower end

i.¶

In [22]:
f <- summary(lm.fit)$fstatistic
p <- pf(f[1],f[2],f[3],lower.tail=F)
p
value: 7.03198902940446e-81

Since the null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between mpg and horsepower while the p-value corresponding to the F-statistic is 7.03198902940446e-81, it can be concluded that the null hypothesis is false and there is a relationship between mpg and horsepower.

ii.¶

In [23]:
paste("Varriability: ",summary(lm.fit)$r.squared * 100, " %")
RSE <- summary(lm.fit)$sigma
mean <- getElement(summary(Auto$mpg), 'Mean')

'Varriability: 60.5948257889435 %'
'Error: 20.9237140669148 %'

With 60.5948257889435 % varriability and 20.9237140669148 % error, horsepower can explain mpg
